\b \cf2 Overview:\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl360\slmult1
\ls2\ilvl0
\b0 \cf0 Wolterstorff aims to give an account of justice as natural rights in order to defend those who have been wronged. He aims to use rights-talk because it \'91brings to speech\'92 the \'91patient-dimension\'92 of moral action, that is, not the one who acts rightly or wrongly but the one wronged or loved. \
\
What is a right? A \'93normative social relationship\'94 (12). What is justice? \'93I think of a social order as just insofar as its members enjoy the goods to which they have rights\'94 (10). The alternative is that justice is \'93natural law for the right ordering of society\'94 \'97 the objective and transcendent agent-dimension rather than the subjective immanent patient-dimension. \
\
What is the issue? 1. It seems to be \'93are there natural rights?\'94 but even right-order theorists can concede that there are. 2. It seems to be \'93are there 
\i inherent 
\i0 natural rights (or only conferred by God, by law, by government, etc.)? But the right order theorist can concede that God has natural rights (Chp 3). 3. It seems to be \'93are there inherent 
\i human 
\i0 natural rights?\'94 \
\
