\b \cf2 Chapter 2. A Contest of Narratives\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl360\slmult1
\ls8\ilvl0
\b0 \cf0 The \'93polemic\'94 that treats justices as right order instead of inherent rights is a narrative. Ockham is blamed as the father of modern rights. \
\
Joan O\'92Donovan and Alistair MacIntyre, Michael Villey, Leo Strauss tell the narrative; Brian Tierney and Charles Reid tell the counter narrative. The 12th and 13th century thinkers like Decretists, popes, and emperors were talking about 
\i ius 
\i0 as both objective law and subjective right (54-55). They spoke of power, faculty, liberties, authority, and justice, as well as \'93right\'94 (57). \
\
Villey\'92s narrative has two \'93main parts\'94 (48). Earlier Latin jurists were not using our concept of right when they used \'91ius,\'92 and that Ockham is somehow the culprit of the decline from Thomism (48-49). \
\
Thirdly, the story goes,  Enlightenment thinkers (HObbes, Locke, etc.) built on this foundation by arguing that the individuals are bearers of subjective rights and \'93the principal task of the state\'94 is to protect those rights (51). This is the \'93possessive individualism\'94 that is the bugbear of the rights-talk-is-bad narrative. \
\
The counter-narrative shows that earlier thinkers 
\i did 
\i0 use \'91ius\'92 in our sense (54ff). It exists in the Roman jurists, according to Donahue, where a right is \'91had\'92 by someone or \'91belongs\'92 to someone (59). Maybe not natural rights but definitely subjective rights. The Church Fathers speak of what is due to the poor, what belongs to them (61).\
\
So what is the real issue? (62). 
\i Whether natural rights are conferred (by God, man, or \'91some objective norm\'92) or inherent
\i0 . \'93Tierney and Reid do not address the issue.\'94\
\
