\pard\pardeftab720\sl360\slmult1
\ls9\ilvl0
\b0 \cf0 The discussion of rights as pernicious moral vocabulary is just the one I have been wanting. He cites and summarizes (in more detail than I could have) exactly the objections I have picked up from here and there. I don\'92t believe in rights. MacIntyre doesn\'92t believe in rights (
\i After Virtue, 
\i0 chp. 6 \'97 \'91Some Consequences of the Failure of the Enlightenment Project\'92). Rights only come into being with the deterioration and collapse of \'93hierarchy, teleology,\'94 a Logo-centric worldview, like buildings collapse in an earthquake. Wolterstorff acknowledges all this narrative. \
\
I\'92m not sure if the word-concept fallacy is not running riot here. If we define rights as \'93normative social relationships\'94 that emphasize the \'93patient-dimension\'94 of those norms (the one suffering wrong) rather than the \'93agent-dimension\'94 (the one doing wrong), then sure, those are Biblical things. But the primary worry I have is the secular grounding of rights he discusses in the antepenultimate chapter. \
\
He says \'93For the right order theorist, the violation of someon\'92s natural rights is never, in itself and as such, the treating of a human being with less than due respect. It is always instead an indicator of the fact that some natural law of objective obligation has been disobeyed. A partisan of right order may point to th eplight of the poor, he may say that their rights are being violated. But pointing to the victims is for him a roundabout way of calling attention to the more fundamental fact that the powerful and the well-to-do are not living up to their obligations\'94 (43). I disagree. \
\
His three criteria for interpreting Biblical teaching on inherent rights make the case easy to argue. \
